T1  - In Search of Attention
AU  - DA, ZHI
AU  - ENGELBERG, JOSEPH
AU  - GAO, PENGJIE
Y1  - 2011/10/01
PY  - 2011
DA  - 2011/10/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2011.01679.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 1461
EP  - 1499
VL  - 66
IS  - 5
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2011.01679.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT We propose a new and direct measure of investor attention using search frequency in Google (Search Volume Index (SVI)). In a sample of Russell 3000 stocks from 2004 to 2008, we find that SVI (1) is correlated with but different from existing proxies of investor attention; (2) captures investor attention in a more timely fashion and (3) likely measures the attention of retail investors. An increase in SVI predicts higher stock prices in the next 2 weeks and an eventual price reversal within the year. It also contributes to the large first-day return and long-run underperformance of IPO stocks.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Free Cash Flow, Issuance Costs, and Stock Prices
AU  - DÉCAMPS, JEAN-PAUL
AU  - MARIOTTI, THOMAS
AU  - ROCHET, JEAN-CHARLES
AU  - VILLENEUVE, STÉPHANE
Y1  - 2011/10/01
PY  - 2011
DA  - 2011/10/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2011.01680.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 1501
EP  - 1544
VL  - 66
IS  - 5
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2011.01680.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT We develop a dynamic model of a firm facing agency costs of free cash flow and external financing costs, and derive an explicit solution for the firm's optimal balance sheet dynamics. Financial frictions affect issuance and dividend policies, the value of cash holdings, and the dynamics of stock prices. The model predicts that the marginal value of cash varies negatively with the stock price, and positively with the volatility of the stock price. This yields novel insights on the asymmetric volatility phenomenon, on risk management policies, and on how business cycles and agency costs affect the volatility of stock returns.
ER  - 

